														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4522649">
									

<p>My own story is probably a bit unconventional. A friend introduced me to this YouTuber called MsBreezy a couple years back, and the channel was mostly about just a couple friends messing around in Garry's Mod. There were a few videos involving the SCP Foundation (mostly 096, 106, and 173), and eventually I decided to look into what the SCP Foundation actually was.</p>
<p>I have to admit, for a long time I didn't even acknowledge the forums, thinking that they were just discussing the articles. I had no idea whether or not the SCP Foundation was actually a real thing, because I was in, like, 6th grade. Imagine how I felt when I first read SCP-2718 and its SCP Declassified article.</p>
<p>I got obsessed with the Foundation for a while. Sometimes I would even skip schoolwork to read the articles. But I lost interest after a little bit, and for a year or so I was just occasionally skimming an article or two every other week.</p>
<p>Finally, a few months ago, I finally dove into the actual writing part of the Foundation. I found out that there was a whole drafting and critting and posting process, and I was <em>really</em> interested. I made an account, read the Newbie Guide, and just binge-read the Guide pages, making a good half dozen drafts before I finally got a page on the mainsite, just last week or so.</p>
<p>Really, I think that I might've done moderately well for a new writer on the site. I already had a really good grasp of the Foundation, from almost two or three years of site lurking. I didn't just dive in immediately; I was on the site for a <em>long</em> time before I made an account.</p>
<p>I have to admit, I never would've thought that watching some channel about silly people playing GMod would lead to me being a member of the SCP Foundation. It's weird how that happens.</p>

							</div>

								
					
