					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/literallymechanical" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2829014); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2829014&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204983" alt="LiterallyMechanical" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2829014)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/literallymechanical" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2829014); return false;" >LiterallyMechanical</a></span> <span class="odate time_1583012823 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">29 Feb 2020 21:47</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4524442">
									

<p>I first heard about the Foundation from a comment about SCP-055 on an entirely unrelated website in 2008, back before there were any four-digit SCPs. I actually have a few (very bad) SCPs that still exist in Series I, under a defunct account. Reading the wiki was a very different experience, back then. There was a lot more blood and gore, a lot less character and plot development, and a lot more bumbling researchers causing containment breaches with their wacky antics. There was definitely a lot of charm to the site back then, and plenty of fascinating articles, but it kind of blurred together. It felt like I was reading the same scp over and over, and I drifted away around 2010.</p>
<p>I poked my nose back in around 2017, more or less out of curiosity and nostalgia. I was amazed to find how much the site had grown and flourished in the intervening years. It's less a repository for creepypasta and more a collaborative storytelling website, where hundreds of authors brought different ideas to the table to create something much greater than the sum of its parts. In a lot of ways, I feel like the wiki grew up, and I'm excited to see where it goes next!</p>

							</div>

								
